JOHANNESBURG – Naspers has raised nearly $10-billion (R117-billion) from selling 2 percent of its stake in Tencent. It was the first time in 17 years that the media giant got rid of some of its shares. Naspers is Tencent's largest shareholder. The funds will go towards strengthening the company’s balance sheet and finance its investment in classifieds, online food delivery and fintech globally. READ: Big spender Naspers is worth less than the sum of its parts The group says it has no plans of further reducing its stake in the IT business. The sale comes a day after Tencent reported that it missed its quarterly revenue estimates. eNCA